In the year 1872, the young José Rizal left his home to continue his studies in Manila. He enrolled at the Ateneo Municipal de Manila,  a school known for its strict discipline and Jesuit methods of teaching.
In this new environment, Rizal faced higher standards of education. Every day was filled with educational challenges and trial of his character.
Under the guidance of his teachers, including Francisco de Paula Sanchez, his skills in science, art, and literature were gradually shaped.
Before long, his diligence and intelligence stood out. From being a quiet student, he became one of the best in his class.
This was where his love for writing began to emerge, poems and essays that reflected his feelings and observations of society.
In 1877, he graduated with a Bachelor of Arts with the highest honors—sobresaliente.
But education did not just give him knowledge... it also opened his mind to a wider world.